In the same way that malloc(0) returns non-NULL, realloc(x, 0) should return a pointer to an allocation of size 0, not NULL.

test case:

#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int
main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
        printf("%p\n", realloc(malloc(1), 0));
}

% ./a.out        
0x0

